      <h2>Why SERP Features Matter for SEO</h2>
      <p>Google has evolved far beyond the classic "10 blue links." Modern SERPs are rich with features that push organic results down the page — or give you new opportunities to appear above them.</p>
      <p>A featured snippet can capture 35% of clicks for informational queries. A local pack dominates the fold for service-based searches. People Also Ask boxes expand the SERP real estate and give you multiple entry points. Videos and images appear for visual queries. If you are not tracking these features, you are flying blind.</p>

      <div class="feature-grid two-col">
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Featured Snippets</h3>
          <p>The "position zero" result that appears above all organic listings. Usually a paragraph, list, or table pulled from a top-ranking page. Captures 35%+ of clicks for informational queries.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>People Also Ask</h3>
          <p>Expandable question boxes that multiply your chances of appearing on page one. Each question links to a different page — one article can rank for multiple PAA questions.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Local Pack</h3>
          <p>The map + 3-business listing that appears for local searches ("dentist near me"). Captures 60%+ of local search clicks. Appears above organic results.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Knowledge Graph</h3>
          <p>The information panel on the right side of the SERP for entities (brands, people, places). Built from structured data, Wikipedia, and trusted sources. Hard to influence but worth monitoring.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

